<subSubSection id="A5D06562FFF3E65FF4EE26B1A650FD90" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="ED7536E9FFF3E65FF4EE26B1A3DFFE2C" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,571]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF4EE26B1A63AFF04" bold="true" box="[199,310,151,175]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF59926B1A587FF04" authorityName="Cao, Wang &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2021" box="[432,651,151,175]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Burmotachinymphes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF59926B1A587FF04" box="[432,651,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Burmotachinymphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF73C26B1A385FF04" authority="Ponomarenko, 1992" authorityName="Ponomarenko" authorityYear="1992" box="[789,1161,151,175]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Tachinymphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF73C26B1A4A1FF04" box="[789,941,151,175]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Tachinymphes</emphasis>
Ponomarenko, 1992
</taxonomicName>
by RP, MA, MP and CuA not distally coalesced in forewing. However, there are some obvious differences between them. [1] In all wings of 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF145269AA68CFF5C" authority=", MA" authorityName="MA" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Burmotachinymphes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF145269AA646FF5C" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Burmotachinymphes</emphasis>
, MA
</taxonomicName>
is simple, MP and CuA are pectinately branched. However, 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF7D326F9A39EFF5C" authorityName="Ponomarenko" authorityYear="1992" box="[1018,1170,223,247]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Tachinymphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF7D326F9A39EFF5C" box="[1018,1170,223,247]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Tachinymphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
generally has more complex venation and more longitudinal branches, and MP and CuA sometimes coalesced in hind wing (e.g., fused or meeting in one point in 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF51E2701A5E3FE94" authority="Nel et al., 2005" authorityName="Nel" authorityYear="2005" box="[311,751,295,319]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Tachinymphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paicheleri">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF51E2701A54DFE94" box="[311,577,295,319]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Tachinymphes paicheleri</emphasis>
Nel 
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF65D270EA5AEFE94" box="[628,674,295,319]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">et al</emphasis>
., 2005
</taxonomicName>
). [2] In 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF76B2701A311FE94" box="[834,1053,295,319]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Burmotachinymphes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF76B2701A311FE94" box="[834,1053,295,319]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Burmotachinymphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the distal marginal branches of MP and CuA have much more and regularly pectinate branches (i.e., the number of branches equal to or more than four), but in 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF49A2749A672FE2C" authority=", MP" authorityName="MP" box="[179,382,367,391]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Tachinymphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF49A2749A647FE2C" box="[179,331,367,391]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Tachinymphes</emphasis>
, MP
</taxonomicName>
and CuA are generally dichotomously forked or with irregularly multiple forks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ED7536E9FFF3E65FF4EE27B5A650FD90" blockId="1.[151,1437,151,571]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">
Besides, the body size, the ratio of wing length to width, and the arrangement of crossveins in the radial area are regarded as the differences between 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF6002791A408FE64" box="[553,772,439,463]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Burmotachinymphes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF6002791A408FE64" box="[553,772,439,463]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Burmotachinymphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF7172791A393FE64" authority="(Cao et al. 2021)" baseAuthorityName="Cao" baseAuthorityYear="2021" box="[830,1183,439,463]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Tachinymphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF7172791A4DAFE64" box="[830,982,439,463]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Tachinymphes</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="895B4B18FFF3E65FF7CF2791A39BFE64" author="Cao, L. R. &amp; Wang, B. &amp; Liu, X. Y." box="[998,1175,439,463]" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" pagination="1" refId="ref2211" refString="Cao, L. R., Wang, B. &amp; Liu, X. Y. (2021) A new genus and species of Mesochrysopidae (Neuroptera) from the mid-Cretaceous Burmese amber. Palaeoentomology, 4 (1), 077 - 084. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / PALAEOENTOMOLOGY. 4.1.12" type="journal article" year="2021">
Cao 
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF035279EA342FE64" box="[1052,1102,439,463]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">et al</emphasis>
. 2021
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The differences in the ratio of wing and the arrangement of crossveins are well supported by the new specimen of this paper, but the wing size of new specimen (forewing more than 
<quantity id="2A329B0CFFF3E65FF61427D9A585FDBC" box="[573,649,511,535]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
by estimation) is indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName id="2ACA4D6AFFF3E65FF06027D9A3EDFDBC" box="[1097,1249,511,535]" class="Insecta" family="Mesochrysopidae" genus="Tachinymphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DFBEEAFBFFF3E65FF06027D9A3EDFDBC" box="[1097,1249,511,535]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="598">Tachinymphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(forewing length about 
<quantity id="2A329B0CFFF3E65FF4F02405A65CFD90" box="[217,336,547,571]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="598" unit="mm" value="20.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="16.0">16–25 mm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
